{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_dexter_ver01/data/42047197/00340588678/1945100101/0351.xml":{"full_text":"Octobcr 1, 1945\nIndustry Can Absorb Pay\nBoosts and Not Reuse the\nPrices on Products\u2014Davis\nBy DONALD MONTGOMERY, Comumer Co lintel, UAW-CIO\nWASHINGTON \u2014\u201cThe door was opened to wide\nspread government-sponsored wage increases this\nweek by Economic Stabilization Director William H.\nDavis/' That\u2019s the magazine Business Week talking;\nissue of September 8.\n\u201cCorporate profits stand to\nbe surprisingly good in 1946.\nThe total might quite con\nceivably top 1944\u2019s $10,000,000,-\n000 by a slight margin. 1 That\u2019s\nBusiness Week also; issue of\nSeptember 1.\n\nThese two statements are big\nnews for organized labor. In\ncreased wages now have official\nbacking. The business outlook\nfor 1946 includes large profits\nout of which higher wages can\nbe paid.\n\nMr. Davis held a press con\nference September 4. He gave\nthe boys a lecture in economics.\nHe showed them that wages not\nonly can be raised, he said it could\nbe done without raising prices. He\nsaid this not only can be done, but\nmust be done if we are going to\nraise the standard of living to a\nfull-employment level within the\nnext few years.\n\nThese statements make plain\nthat Mr. Davis is going to remove\nthe barrier to higher wages In\npresent stabilization policy! He\nproposes to see that wage rises do\nnot get defeated at OPA by the\nautomatic price raising devices of\nthat agency.\nsee\nHis statements also offer a chal\nlenge to labor. He proposes, in ef\nfect, that labor can get real wage\nincreases only when prices do not\nrise to wipe out the benefit of the\nhigher wages. He tells that labor\nthat is possible, and tells us to go\nto it\u2014with his help.\nsee\nMost important of all, however,\nis the formula for a prosperour\nand vigorous economy of the fu\nture that Mr. Davis sets forth.\nHe shows that our rising standard\nof living has always come in the\npast'through wages that went up\nfaster than prices. He turns to the\nfuture and says we can still do\nthat. He suggests that wages must\ngo up 40 to 50 per cent in the next\nfive years, without a rise in prices.\nThis, he pointed out to the report\nITW& WWTIN omw Y CO (NEXT STEPW*3 TO FIGHT FOR FREE PUBUC fff** Fl6 lr 10,16 MO BITTER. Biff...\nIT STARTED THE FIRST LABOR *ft>oCAT)ON V**S Of*y R*? TMOSJE WHO COULD AFFORD LAR6 EtV THROU6H THE EFFORTS OF LA BOR/\nA*\u00ae*,\"\u2122* MECHANICS FREE CHILDREN OF THE WORKERS 6DT NONE Ar ALL, BV 1850 IT WAS WON THROUGHOUT THE\nPRESS\u2019* AND THE FIRST LABOR I o|Affn y N -f*up\u00a3p SCHOOLS* LIKETMiS.... lli 1111 l t i i\npZ&ii* mSSmEWTwSaD y e \"TV i y r 7w~ ALL PCMOOWNty IS BASED ON UNIVERSAL EDO- NOW. RECITE THE \\WE MOLD M SOMEDAY\nT SSrdUag ID MRSENMOR IT MUST ME FREE, y DECLARATION OF IN- THESE TRUTHs\\ WELL\nLily WILD FIRE THROUGH iHb poNT KNOW WWF I BOTHER ASKED WO >Q AMO NOM-S\u20acCTAf?IAN V DEPENDENCE' JTO BE SELF* EVEN\nN *^2L m u .ar m iA.ouou\u00df teachwo bwto mks R D ev.osnt.tkw\n|MOI IIWM| s a j WfK NCTT\ners, is the only way to provide a\nmarket for the products of full\nemployment. Therefore it is the\nonly way private industry can\nachieve full employment.\n\nIn saying that the road to pros\nperity is through higher wages\nDavis really hurt the feelings of\nthe front-men for high capital who\nhave always said the road to pros\nperity is through higher profits.\n\nThe New York Times screamed\nmurder, called the Davis formula\n\u201cblack magic.\" The National Asso\nciation of Manufacturers said he\nwas destroying confidence and ask\ning the impossible.\n\nActually, the figure of 40 to 50\nper cent wage Increase in five\nyears which Davis used to illus\ntrate his formula is conservative.\nAs the NAM gentleman admits, la\nbor productivity has been increas\ning normally at 4 per cent a year.\nIf this normal rate were reflected\nin higher wages, so as to catch up\nwith the war lag in wage rates and\nthen continue for the next five\nyears, we would have an increase\nof better than 4/6 per cent. War\nimprovements in technology and\npostwar production at full-employ\nment levels would easily add an\nother 10 per cent to labor produc\ntivity, which also could be reflected\nin higher wages or lower prices or\nboth.\nsee\nDavis Is conservative in his fig\nures. -He is a radical, however,\nwhen he suggests that wages are\nnot just something which manage\nment hands down out of profits\nwhen it feels like it. He i& a revo\nlutionary when he shows that\nneither labor, nor management nor\nfree enterprise can produce a high\nstandard of living unless rising\nwages are available to pay for it\nand can buy it at stable prices,\nsee\nIn short, Mr. Davis has spoken a\nmouthful. Will his valiant and\nprophetic words fall on deaf ears?\nUp until now response has come\nonly from those who read in his\nprophesy a new kind oi world in\nwhich they will no longer sit un\nchallenged on the top of the heap.\nThey don\u2019t like it, and are saying\nso noisily.\nUNITED AUTOMOBILE WORKER\nSecretary Ctddei Say\u00bb\nONE FOR ALL AND ALL\nFQRONE\nAfter a month of peace we know\nvery little more than we did before\nabout what conditions are going to\nbe like during the postwar period.\nIn the automobile industry, recon\nversion is proceeding about as ex\npected with managements in many\ninstances assuming a very dicta\ntorial attitude in their negotiations\nwith labor. We have no doubt that\nmuch of this is all part of a planned\ncampaign to weaken and, if pos\nsible, destroy our union.\nWorkers are being deliberately\nprovoked in the hope that we will go\nout on strike and in so doing use up\nmuch of our economic strength. In\nother words, our union would be dis\nsipating its strength at the very time\nwhen management don't care\nwhether their plants are in operation\nor not.\nEVERY PRECAUTION MUST BE\nTAKEN TO SEE THAT WE DON'T\nFALL INTO THE TRAPS THAT ARE\nBEING SO CAREFULLY LAID. AS\nWE SAID IN OUR LAST COLUMN\nWE SHOULD BE MILITANT AND\nAGGRESSIVE BUT WE MUST NOT\nLET OUR ENTHUSIASM RUN AWAY\nWITH OUR BETTER JUDGMENTS.\nNow as never before we must act\nin unison if we are to obtain for the\nworkers a higher standard of living.\nA union of a million members has\ntremendous economic power pro\nviding it is used at the proper time\nand in the proper place, but our\nmaximum strength cannot be mo\nbilized unless every worker and\nevery lodal union adheres to the\npolicies and program of the Interna\ntional union.\nThe International Executive Board\nhas mapped out a program which\nwe believe to be the proper one to\nfollow during the days ahead. THE\nSUCCESS OF THE PROGRAM HOW-\nBy\n.GEORGE F.\nADDES\nSecretary-\nTreasurer\nUAW\nCIO\nEVER DEPENDS ENTIRELY UPON\nTHE KIND OF DISCIPLINE THERE IS\nWITHIN OUR UNION. UNAUTHOR\nIZED STRIKES AND STOPPAGES OF\nWORK MUST CEASE. Furthermore\nthere would be none if every union\nmember lived up to the Constitution.\nIrresponsible action on the part of\nlocal unions and failure to abide by\nthe Constitution could very well\nwreck the union. Division among\nourselves, with each local union en\ndeavoring to settle its problems in its\nown way is exactly what manage\nments want. Let us not kid ourselves,\nanti-labor forces would like nothing\nbetter than to see our union split up\ninto hundreds of small federated\nlocal, unions.\nDon't let us forget that our armed\nforces defeated Germany and Japan\nbecause there was coordination of\neffort. Defeat might very well have\ncome upon us had each division in\nthe services decided to carry on the\nfight in whatever way it thought\nbest.\nSo it is with our union. If we are\nto win the fight for more wages and\na better living standard we must\nwork and fight together. The future\nwelfare of million workers should\nand must not be jeopardized by the\nirresponsible actions of a few people.\nWE SINCERELY HOPE THAT ALL\nOF OUR MEMBERSHIP WILL AWA\nKEN TO A SENSE OF THEIR RE\nSPONSIBILITY AND THAT DURING\nTHE DAYS TO COME WE WILL GO\nFORWARD ONE FOR ALL AND ALL\nFOR ONE.\nPAGE 7","height":"25332","width":"17031"}}
